{
  "catdef": "1.4",
  "orgdef": "0.3.0",
  "type": "orgdef:Organization",
  "id": "oagp-family-open-standard",
  "name": "OAGP-Family Open Standard (Canonical Template)",
  "version": "1.1.0",

  "mission": "[SLOT: 1–2 sentences stating what THIS spec defines and the open machine-readable artifact it produces. Pick the example shape that matches your spec's category — bootstrap-shaped (loading-AI-into-role), coordinative (inter-position handoff), or substrate (format-providing) — and adapt: BOOTSTRAP example: 'Define X in an open, machine-readable way that bootstraps any AI worker into Y with zero context backfill.' COORDINATIVE example: 'Define X-message exchange between positions in an open, machine-readable way that bootstraps a recipient AI session into an inter-position handoff with zero context backfill.' SUBSTRATE example: 'Define X in an open, machine-readable way that provides the substrate format on which consumer specs build.']",

  "vision": "Part of the Open Agentic Governance Pattern (OAGP) family — alongside catdef, roledef, orgdef, and memodef — defining the pattern of [SLOT: noun-phrase naming what aspect of AI-first organization this spec addresses]. The primary reader of [SLOT: this spec's primary artifact type] is an AI; [SLOT: any spec-specific framing of the cross-org or cross-runtime use case].",

  "scope": "[SLOT: scope statement — what this spec covers and explicitly excludes. Reference adjacent OAGP-family specs and what's out of scope. Example shape: 'The X schema, conformance test suite, canonical-X library, and reference implementations. Out of scope: enforcing what consumers build (content-neutral), runtime infrastructure (specification only), substrate-level concerns belonging to catdef.']",

  "governance_model": "Bounded AI authority + human Director ratification. The [SLOT: spec-name]-strategist (AI role) holds delegated authority for design decisions; the [SLOT: spec-name]-maintainer (AI role, separate seat) drafts spec text and conformance fixtures; the human Director holds final tiebreaker authority on every merge, version bump, and governance change. Mirrors the catdef-family pattern.",

  "values": [
    {
      "name": "openness",
      "description": "[SLOT: spec-name] is fundamentally open — a pattern, not a product. No vendor lock-in, no privileged implementer, no proprietary extensions in the core spec. All AI runtimes (Anthropic, OpenAI, xAI, Google, future) are equal citizens.",
      "rationale": "Adoption depends on equal-citizen treatment of all implementers; vendor capture would defeat the standard's purpose. Forks are welcome — anyone can publish their own [SLOT: spec-name] library at any URL using the same format."
    },
    {
      "name": "completeness",
      "description": "[SLOT: spec's primary artifact] MUST be sufficient — alone or composed with other OAGP-family artifacts — for a fresh AI runtime to act on its content with zero context backfill.",
      "rationale": "Hallucination-prevention rule, not aesthetic preference. The primary reader is a machine; null context invites confabulation. A [SLOT: artifact-class] missing required structural content forces the AI to either guess or ask the user, which violates the zero-friction bar."
    }
  ],

  "red_lines": [
    {
      "rule": "No NULL-context [SLOT: spec's primary artifact type] accepted by the spec, the validator, or the canonical [SLOT: spec-specific facilitator name if applicable, otherwise 'authoring tool'].",
      "rationale": "Technical, not aesthetic — null context causes hallucination in the primary (machine) reader. The MUST-have-substantive-[SLOT: charter/equivalent for this spec] rule is a hallucination-prevention rule, not a quality preference."
    },
    {
      "rule": "No content policing of consumers.",
      "rationale": "What organizations choose to build using the [SLOT: spec-name] pattern is their business, not the spec's. [SLOT: spec-name] governs the pattern's integrity, not the morality of its applications. Curation happens at the LIBRARY level (canonical inclusion), not the SPEC level."
    }
  ],

  "recommended_patterns": {
    "general": [
      {
        "pattern": "Senior strategist role separation",
        "description": "Specs SHOULD have a senior strategist role distinct from execution roles (maintainer, implementor), so each position stays in its lane.",
        "rationale": "Same reason developers shouldn't do their own security testing — bounded scope per role enables clean handoffs and prevents authority concentration."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Two-section charter discipline",
        "description": "Organize orgdef content into two implicit sections: 'how this org operates' (mission, vision, values, governance, positions, relationships, red_lines) vs 'what we recommend for orgs using this pattern' (recommended_patterns). The two sections serve different audiences.",
        "rationale": "First section orients a reader joining this spec org; second section guides anyone deriving a new org from this one as a template. Conflating them muddles both audiences."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Recursive self-describing v1 milestone",
        "description": "Treat 'this very orgdef exists as a valid, self-describing artifact in the org folder' as the spec's v1 success criterion.",
        "rationale": "If the pattern can't bootstrap its own author, it can't bootstrap anyone. Self-description is the most demanding test case for a standards project."
      }
    ],
    "recommended_roles": [
      {
        "role": "human-director",
        "priority": "MUST",
        "why": "Bounded-authority discipline requires a human ratifier."
      },
      {
        "role": {
          "id": "senior-open-standards-strategist",
          "version": "1.0.0",
          "url": "https://roledef.org/roledefs/senior-open-standards-strategist.openthing"
        },
        "priority": "MUST",
        "why": "Library-curation, scope-narrowing, pattern-promotion calls."
      },
      {
        "role": "[SLOT: spec-name]-maintainer",
        "priority": "MUST",
        "why": "Drafts spec text, walks SCHEMA validations, files decision artifacts."
      },
      {
        "role": "canonical-implementor",
        "priority": "SHOULD",
        "why": "Reference renderers and validators are how the spec gets dogfooded."
      }
    ]
  },

  "v1_success_criterion": "[SLOT: spec-name] ships v1 when this very orgdef exists as a valid, self-describing orgdef:Organization artifact in the [SLOT: spec-name] org folder, conformant to a published [SLOT: spec-name] SCHEMA.md — proving the pattern can describe itself using itself.",

  "positions": [
    {
      "id": "director",
      "name": "Director",
      "description": "[SLOT: human Director with final tiebreaker authority. No role_definition (humans are not derived from roledefs). Derivers replace this with their actual Director's name or leave generic.]"
    },
    {
      "id": "strategist",
      "name": "Strategist",
      "description": "[SLOT: derive a job artifact from senior-open-standards-strategist specialized to your spec, then reference here via job_definition. The job artifact lives in your-org/jobs/strategist.openthing per the filesystem convention.]"
    },
    {
      "id": "maintainer",
      "name": "Maintainer",
      "description": "[SLOT: derive a job artifact for [spec-name]-maintainer (drafts spec text, walks SCHEMA validations, files decision artifacts). The job artifact lives in your-org/jobs/maintainer.openthing.]"
    },
    {
      "id": "canonical-implementor",
      "name": "Canonical Implementor",
      "description": "[SLOT: OPTIONAL. Derive a job artifact for canonical-implementor specialized to your spec (reference renderers, validators, test fixtures). The job artifact lives in your-org/jobs/canonical-implementor.openthing. Omit if your spec doesn't need this role.]"
    }
  ],

  "relationships": [
    {
      "type": "reports_to",
      "from": "strategist",
      "to": "director",
      "description": "[SLOT: standard inherited; strategist holds delegated authority, Director ratifies decisions/merges/version-bumps/governance-changes]"
    },
    {
      "type": "directs",
      "from": "strategist",
      "to": "maintainer",
      "description": "[SLOT: standard inherited; strategist makes calls, maintainer drafts spec text in support of those calls]"
    },
    {
      "type": "directs",
      "from": "strategist",
      "to": "canonical-implementor",
      "description": "[SLOT: standard inherited if implementor position present; strategist sets direction for canonical tooling priorities]"
    }
  ],

  "metadata": {
    "kind": "canonical-template",
    "authors": [
      "orgdef-strategist <orgdef-strategist@orgdef.org>"
    ],
    "license": "MIT",
    "created": "2026-04-26",
    "extracted_from": "Generalized from orgdef-spec/orgdef-spec-org/orgdef.openthing v1.0.0, the dogfood orgdef that proved out the pattern. Generalization preserves values, red_lines, and recommended_patterns verbatim (those are the load-bearing OAGP-family invariants); replaces orgdef-specific content (mission, scope, positions specifics) with [SLOT:...] placeholders for derivers to fill.",
    "homepage": "https://orgdef.org/canonical-orgs/oagp-family-open-standard",
    "repository": "https://github.com/orgdef-spec/orgdef/blob/main/canonical-orgs/oagp-family-open-standard.openthing",
    "history": [
      {
        "version": "1.0.0",
        "date": "2026-04-26",
        "change": "Initial canonical template, extracted from orgdef-spec/orgdef-spec-org/orgdef.openthing v1.0.0. First entry in the canonical-orgs/ library. Submitted alongside the canonical-orgs-library proposal that establishes the canonical-orgs/ directory + metadata.kind field + derivation conventions."
      },
      {
        "version": "1.1.0",
        "date": "2026-04-30",
        "change": "Patches per orgdef-spec/orgdef-spec-org/decisions/proposal-canonical-template-v1.1-and-placement-convention.md, grounded in three independent derivations (memodef-spec, roledef-spec, catdef-spec). P1 mission slot offers three example shapes (bootstrap / coordinative / substrate) per triple-confirmed bootstrap-bias finding. P2 vision drops the orgdef-specific 'introduction artifact between organizations' clause. P3 vision two-clause shape documented in instantiation_notes. P4 completeness value rephrased to handle bundle-shaped, single-artifact-shaped, and substrate-shaped specs uniformly. P5 recommended_roles representational convention formalized in instantiation_notes. P6 v1_success_criterion two example shapes (forward-looking-recursive, retrospective-Gordian-knot) acknowledged in instantiation_notes. P7 Director-elicitation-step + at-read-back-correction patterns promoted to canonical workflow guidance in instantiation_notes. P8 governance terminology vocabulary mismatch note added to instantiation_notes. P9 REPLACE convention soft note about family-resemblance added to instantiation_notes (no new SLOT-FILL category). P10 placement convention updated from <spec>/<spec>-org/orgdef.openthing to <spec>/org/<id>.openthing — matches catdef-family library convention; preserves cross-spec aggregation."
      }
    ],
    "derivation_conventions": "Per the additive-only derivation discipline per orgdef SCHEMA.md: derivers MAY add to values, red_lines, recommended_patterns; SHOULD NOT remove canonical entries (those are family-level invariants). Mission, scope, positions, relationships are derivation-specific (REPLACE, don't extend) — but REPLACE for mission/vision still expects family-resemblance in shape (zero-context-backfill framing, OAGP-family identification, primary-reader-is-AI), even when the noun-phrases differ. Vision and governance_model are inheritable-or-refinable (most derivations will refine slightly; major deviation should be discussed with the orgdef-strategist). Empirically (across three v1.0.0 derivations), REPLACE-labeled fields ended up echoing canonical structure closely; the soft-note-about-family-resemblance solves the friction without requiring a new SLOT-FILL category.",
    "instantiation_notes": "When deriving from this template:\n\n(1) Replace all [SLOT:...] placeholders with concrete content. Mission's three example shapes (bootstrap / coordinative / substrate) cover the empirically observed OAGP-family categories; pick the closest match to your spec's category.\n\n(2) Add metadata.derived_from pointing at this canonical artifact (id + version + url).\n\n(3) Author your own positions and relationships (deriving job artifacts from senior-open-standards-strategist and forthcoming canonical roledefs for maintainer/implementor). Place job artifacts at <spec>/org/jobs/<job-id>.openthing per the placement convention.\n\n(4) Set metadata.kind to 'operational'.\n\n(5) Optionally add new entries to values, red_lines, recommended_patterns (do NOT remove canonical entries).\n\n(6) Optionally refine vision and governance_model within bounds (preserve family-resemblance in shape).\n\n(7) Vision is one slot doing two jobs: a noun-phrase first clause (specific to your spec) and a primary-reader-is-AI invariant clause (mostly boilerplate). Fill the noun-phrase precisely; preserve the boilerplate's shape.\n\n(8) recommended_roles representation: use bare-string `role` values for in-org roles or for roles whose canonical roledef hasn't yet been published; use full coordinate objects ({id, version, url}) for externally-published-and-stable roles per the metadata.role_definition shape.\n\n(9) v1_success_criterion may be expressed prospectively (forward-looking-recursive: 'v1 ships when this orgdef exists as a self-describing artifact') OR retrospectively (Gordian-knot: 'v1 has already been achieved; here's the evidence'). Mature standards that shipped before the orgdef bootstrap typically use the retrospective shape. The canonical's recursive example was authored by orgdef-spec describing its OWN v1; follow-on specs may legitimately differ.\n\n(10) Governance terminology: derivers MAY rename a recommended-roles seat for spec-internal-naming-convention alignment (e.g., catdef's 'Chief Strategist' refers to the senior-open-standards-strategist role under different naming) as long as the role's bounded-authority discipline is preserved.\n\n(11) Placement convention (P10): operational orgdef artifacts live at <project>/org/<id>.openthing per catdef-family library convention. Job artifacts live at <project>/org/jobs/<job-id>.openthing. The legacy <project>/<orgname>-org/ convention is deprecated for new derivations; existing legacy-placed artifacts should migrate when convenient.\n\n(12) High-context mode workflow: when most slots are inferable from materials, expect TWO Director-driven calls per derivation — (a) elicit ONE explicit Director answer for the slot most likely not inferable from materials BEFORE delivering the read-back (typically v1_success_criterion or a Director-specific weight); (b) expect ONE additional inference-not-fact correction to surface AT read-back time, even if the rest of the artifact is approved as-is. Plan for both, not just the pre-read-back elicitation."
  }
}
